# Conventional Commits

All commit messages in this project follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format and must be written in **English**.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

- **type** (required): kind of change
- **scope** (optional): part of the codebase
- **description** (required): short imperative description, lowercase after the colon

## Allowed types

| Type       | Use for |
|-----------|---------|
| `feat`    | New feature |
| `fix`     | Bug fix |
| `docs`    | Documentation only |
| `style`   | Formatting (no code change, e.g. whitespace, semicolons) |
| `refactor`| Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature |
| `test`    | Adding or updating tests |
| `chore`   | Maintenance (deps, config, build, etc.) |

## Examples

**Good:**
- `feat(auth): add email login`
- `fix(api): return 404 for missing query params`
- `docs: update README and deploy instructions`
- `chore(deps): upgrade astro to 4.x`

**Bad:**
- `Added login` → use `feat: add login`
- `fixed bug` → use `fix: [short description of the bug]`
- `Changes` → use a type, e.g. `chore: various changes`

## Rules

1. Use imperative mood in the description: "add" not "added".
2. No period at the end of the subject line.
3. First line max ~72 characters; use the body for more detail.
4. For breaking changes: add `BREAKING CHANGE:` in the footer or use `!` after type/scope (e.g. `feat!: new API`).

When suggesting or writing commit messages, always use this format and write in English.
